### Task
Write C++ coroutines (C++20) for a lazy generator.

### Solution
```cpp
#include <coroutine>
#include <iostream>

template<typename T>
struct Generator {
    struct promise_type {
        T current;
        auto yield_value(T v){ current=v; return std::suspend_always{}; }
        auto initial_suspend(){ return std::suspend_always{}; }
        auto final_suspend() noexcept { return std::suspend_always{}; }
        Generator get_return_object(){
            return Generator{std::coroutine_handle<promise_type>::from_promise(*this)}; }
        void unhandled_exception(){ std::terminate(); }
        void return_void(){}
    };
    std::coroutine_handle<promise_type> handle;
    bool next(){ handle.resume(); return !handle.done(); }
    T    value(){ return handle.promise().current; }
    ~Generator(){ if(handle) handle.destroy(); }
};

Generator<int> range(int lo, int hi) {
    for (int i=lo; i<hi; ++i) co_yield i;
}

int main() {
    auto gen = range(0, 5);
    while (gen.next())
        std::cout << gen.value() << ' ';  // 0 1 2 3 4
}
```
co_yield suspends the coroutine and transfers a value to the caller. The promise_type customises the coroutine machinery. Each resume() runs until the next co_yield or return. The coroutine frame lives on the heap.

### Task
Implement a C++ memory-mapped file reader using platform APIs.

### Solution
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string_view>
#ifdef _WIN32
#  include <windows.h>
#else
#  include <sys/mman.h>
#  include <fcntl.h>
#  include <sys/stat.h>
#  include <unistd.h>
#endif

std::string_view mmap_file(const char* path) {
#ifdef _WIN32
    HANDLE hFile = CreateFileA(path, GENERIC_READ, FILE_SHARE_READ,
                               nullptr, OPEN_EXISTING, 0, nullptr);
    LARGE_INTEGER sz; GetFileSizeEx(hFile, &sz);
    HANDLE hMap = CreateFileMappingA(hFile, nullptr, PAGE_READONLY, 0,0,nullptr);
    void* ptr = MapViewOfFile(hMap, FILE_MAP_READ, 0, 0, 0);
    CloseHandle(hFile); CloseHandle(hMap);
    return {static_cast<const char*>(ptr), static_cast<size_t>(sz.QuadPart)};
#else
    int fd = open(path, O_RDONLY);
    struct stat st; fstat(fd, &st);
    void* ptr = mmap(nullptr, st.st_size, PROT_READ, MAP_PRIVATE, fd, 0);
    close(fd);
    return {static_cast<const char*>(ptr), static_cast<size_t>(st.st_size)};
#endif
}

int main() {
    auto view = mmap_file("large.txt");
    std::cout << "Size: " << view.size() << '\n';
}
```
Memory-mapped files let the OS page in data on demand — no explicit read() calls, no intermediate buffer. For read-heavy workloads this beats fread by avoiding a kernel-to-userspace copy. The OS uses the page cache directly.

### Task
Write a Go function that reads lines from a file concurrently using goroutines and a channel.

### Solution
```go
package main
import (
    "bufio"
    "fmt"
    "os"
)

func readLines(path string) (<-chan string, <-chan error) {
    lines := make(chan string, 100)
    errc  := make(chan error, 1)
    go func() {
        defer close(lines)
        defer close(errc)
        f, err := os.Open(path)
        if err != nil { errc <- err; return }
        defer f.Close()
        sc := bufio.NewScanner(f)
        for sc.Scan() {
            lines <- sc.Text()
        }
        if err := sc.Err(); err != nil { errc <- err }
    }()
    return lines, errc
}

func main() {
    lines, errc := readLines("data.txt")
    for line := range lines {
        fmt.Println(line)
    }
    if err := <-errc; err != nil {
        fmt.Fprintln(os.Stderr, err)
    }
}
```
The goroutine closes both channels on exit — ranging over a closed channel terminates cleanly. A buffered channel (100) decouples the producer from the consumer, preventing blocking on slow processors.

### Task
Implement a Go HTTP server with middleware for logging and request ID injection.

### Solution
```go
package main
import (
    "fmt"
    "log"
    "net/http"
    "time"
    "math/rand"
)

type Middleware func(http.Handler) http.Handler

func chain(h http.Handler, mw ...Middleware) http.Handler {
    for i := len(mw)-1; i >= 0; i-- { h = mw[i](h) }
    return h
}

func logging(next http.Handler) http.Handler {
    return http.HandlerFunc(func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
        start := time.Now()
        next.ServeHTTP(w, r)
        log.Printf("%s %s %v", r.Method, r.URL.Path, time.Since(start))
    })
}

func requestID(next http.Handler) http.Handler {
    return http.HandlerFunc(func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
        id := fmt.Sprintf("%x", rand.Int63())
        w.Header().Set("X-Request-ID", id)
        next.ServeHTTP(w, r)
    })
}

func main() {
    mux := http.NewServeMux()
    mux.HandleFunc("/", func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
        fmt.Fprintln(w, "Hello")
    })
    log.Fatal(http.ListenAndServe(":8080", chain(mux, requestID, logging)))
}
```
chain applies middleware right-to-left so the first argument wraps outermost. The pattern is idiomatic Go — no framework needed. Each middleware calls next.ServeHTTP to pass control down the chain.

### Task
Write Go code implementing a worker pool with a fixed number of goroutines.

### Solution
```go
package main
import (
    "fmt"
    "sync"
)

func workerPool(numWorkers int, jobs <-chan int) <-chan int {
    results := make(chan int, numWorkers)
    var wg sync.WaitGroup
    for i := 0; i < numWorkers; i++ {
        wg.Add(1)
        go func() {
            defer wg.Done()
            for j := range jobs {
                results <- j * j  // simulate work
            }
        }()
    }
    go func() { wg.Wait(); close(results) }()
    return results
}

func main() {
    jobs := make(chan int, 20)
    for i := 1; i <= 10; i++ { jobs <- i }
    close(jobs)

    for r := range workerPool(4, jobs) {
        fmt.Println(r)
    }
}
```
WaitGroup tracks how many goroutines are running. A separate goroutine waits for all workers then closes results — this is the canonical Go fan-out/fan-in pattern. Closing the jobs channel signals workers to exit their range loop.

