The select races between the result channel and ctx.Done(). Cancellation propagates through the entire call tree — pass the context to every downstream call. Always call the cancel function (deferred) to release timer resources even if the context times out.

### Task
Implement Go generics (1.18+) for a type-safe Map and Filter.

### Solution
```go
package main
import "fmt"

func Map[T, U any](s []T, f func(T) U) []U {
    out := make([]U, len(s))
    for i, v := range s { out[i] = f(v) }
    return out
}

func Filter[T any](s []T, pred func(T) bool) []T {
    var out []T
    for _, v := range s {
        if pred(v) { out = append(out, v) }
    }
    return out
}

func Reduce[T, Acc any](s []T, init Acc, f func(Acc, T) Acc) Acc {
    acc := init
    for _, v := range s { acc = f(acc, v) }
    return acc
}

func main() {
    nums := []int{1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6}
    evens  := Filter(nums, func(n int) bool { return n%2 == 0 })
    squares := Map(evens, func(n int) int { return n * n })
    sum    := Reduce(squares, 0, func(a, b int) int { return a + b })
    fmt.Println(evens, squares, sum)  // [2 4 6] [4 16 36] 56
}
```
Type parameters [T, U any] allow the compiler to infer concrete types from usage — no explicit instantiation needed. Go generics use type inference, so Map(nums, func(n int) string{...}) infers T=int, U=string automatically.

### Task
Write Go code for a concurrent rate limiter using time.Ticker.

### Solution
```go
package main
import (
    "fmt"
    "time"
)

func rateLimiter(rps int) func() {
    ticker := time.NewTicker(time.Second / time.Duration(rps))
    stop   := make(chan struct{})
    wait   := make(chan struct{}, rps)

    go func() {
        defer ticker.Stop()
        for {
            select {
            case <-ticker.C:
                select {
                case wait <- struct{}{}: // slot available
                default:               // backpressure
                }
            case <-stop:
                return
            }
        }
    }()

    return func() {
        <-wait  // block until a slot is available
    }
}

func main() {
    limit := rateLimiter(5) // 5 requests/sec
    for i := 0; i < 10; i++ {
        limit()
        fmt.Printf("request %d at %v\n", i, time.Now().Format("15:04:05.000"))
    }
}
```
time.Ticker fires at a fixed interval, providing tokens into a buffered channel. Callers block on <-wait until a token is available. The buffered channel size limits burst capacity.

### Task
Implement Go sync.Map for a concurrent cache with expiry.

### Solution
```go
package main
import (
    "fmt"
    "sync"
    "time"
)

type entry struct {
    value     interface{}
    expiresAt time.Time
}

type TTLCache struct {
    data sync.Map
}

func (c *TTLCache) Set(key string, value interface{}, ttl time.Duration) {
    c.data.Store(key, entry{value, time.Now().Add(ttl)})
}

func (c *TTLCache) Get(key string) (interface{}, bool) {
    v, ok := c.data.Load(key)
    if !ok { return nil, false }
    e := v.(entry)
    if time.Now().After(e.expiresAt) {
        c.data.Delete(key)
        return nil, false
    }
    return e.value, true
}

func main() {
    c := &TTLCache{}
    c.Set("k", "hello", 100*time.Millisecond)
    v, _ := c.Get("k")
    fmt.Println(v)        // hello
    time.Sleep(200 * time.Millisecond)
    _, ok := c.Get("k")
    fmt.Println(ok)       // false
}
```
sync.Map is safe for concurrent read/write without external locking — optimised for read-heavy workloads. Lazy expiry (check on Get) avoids a background goroutine for simple use cases.

