    // FnOnce: captures String (not Copy), can only be called once
    let msg = String::from("hello");
    let greet = move || msg.to_uppercase();  // moves msg into closure
    println!("{}", apply_once(greet));

    // FnMut: mutable state
    let counter = make_counter();
    println!("{:?}", apply_mut(counter, 5));  // [1,2,3,4,5]

    // Fn: pure — can be called any number of times
    let factor = 3;
    println!("{:?}", apply(|x| x * factor, &[1,2,3,4]));
}
```
FnOnce can be called once (consumes captured values), FnMut can be called multiple times mutably (make_counter), Fn can be called any number of times immutably. Every closure implements at least FnOnce. move forces capture by value even for Copy types.

### Task
Write Rust code using lifetimes to implement a string splitter struct.

### Solution
```rust
struct Split<'a> {
    remainder: &'a str,
    delimiter: &'a str,
}

impl<'a> Split<'a> {
    fn new(s: &'a str, delim: &'a str) -> Self {
        Self { remainder: s, delimiter: delim }
    }
}

impl<'a> Iterator for Split<'a> {
    type Item = &'a str;

    fn next(&mut self) -> Option<Self::Item> {
        if let Some(pos) = self.remainder.find(self.delimiter) {
            let item = &self.remainder[..pos];
            self.remainder = &self.remainder[pos + self.delimiter.len()..];
            Some(item)
        } else if self.remainder.is_empty() {
            None
        } else {
            let item = self.remainder;
            self.remainder = "";
            Some(item)
        }
    }
}

fn main() {
    let parts: Vec<_> = Split::new("a,bb,ccc,d", ",").collect();
    println!("{:?}", parts);  // ["a", "bb", "ccc", "d"]
}
```
The lifetime 'a ties the slices returned from next() to the lifetime of the original string — the borrow checker ensures the source string outlives the Split iterator. All returned &str slices are zero-copy views into the original data.

### Task
Implement Rust proc_macro-free derive using trait implementations for Display and From.

### Solution
```rust
use std::fmt;

#[derive(Debug, Clone, PartialEq)]
struct Celsius(f64);

#[derive(Debug, Clone, PartialEq)]
struct Fahrenheit(f64);

impl fmt::Display for Celsius {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut fmt::Formatter) -> fmt::Result {
        write!(f, "{:.1}\u{00B0}C", self.0)
    }
}

impl fmt::Display for Fahrenheit {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut fmt::Formatter) -> fmt::Result {
        write!(f, "{:.1}\u{00B0}F", self.0)
    }
}

impl From<Celsius> for Fahrenheit {
    fn from(c: Celsius) -> Self { Fahrenheit(c.0 * 9.0/5.0 + 32.0) }
}

impl From<Fahrenheit> for Celsius {
    fn from(f: Fahrenheit) -> Self { Celsius((f.0 - 32.0) * 5.0/9.0) }
}

fn main() {
    let boiling = Celsius(100.0);
    let f: Fahrenheit = boiling.clone().into();
    println!("{} = {}", boiling, f);  // 100.0C = 212.0F
    let back: Celsius = f.into();
    println!("{}", back);            // 100.0C
}
```
Newtype wrappers (Celsius(f64)) give compile-time type safety — you can't accidentally pass Fahrenheit where Celsius is expected. From<T> automatically provides Into<T> via a blanket impl in the standard library.

