PathBuf is an owned, mutable path. This manual parse illustrates what clap automates: argument matching, type coercion, and defaults. With clap derive, the struct is annotated and all this parsing is generated at compile time.

### Task
Implement Rust unsafe code for a zero-copy string split using raw pointers.

### Solution
```rust
fn split_at_byte(s: &str, byte_pos: usize) -> (&str, &str) {
    assert!(s.is_char_boundary(byte_pos), "not a char boundary");
    // Safe: we checked char boundary; slices share the same allocation
    (&s[..byte_pos], &s[byte_pos..])
}

// Demonstrate unsafe: manually construct a &str from raw parts
fn from_utf8_unchecked_demo(bytes: &[u8]) -> &str {
    // SAFETY: caller guarantees bytes is valid UTF-8
    unsafe { std::str::from_utf8_unchecked(bytes) }
}

fn main() {
    let text = "Hello, World!";
    let (left, right) = split_at_byte(text, 7);
    println!("{:?} {:?}", left, right);  // "Hello, " "World!"

    let bytes = b"valid UTF-8";
    // Using unsafe only when safe API doesn't exist or is too slow
    let s = from_utf8_unchecked_demo(bytes);
    println!("{}", s);
}
```
is_char_boundary() is the safety check that makes the slice split valid — splitting mid-codepoint would create invalid UTF-8. from_utf8_unchecked is faster than from_utf8 (no validation) but the caller must uphold the invariant. SAFETY comments document the contract.

### Task
Write a Rust program using rayon for data-parallel processing.

### Solution
```rust
use rayon::prelude::*;

fn is_prime(n: u64) -> bool {
    if n < 2 { return false; }
    if n == 2 { return true; }
    if n % 2 == 0 { return false; }
    let sqrt = (n as f64).sqrt() as u64;
    !(3..=sqrt).step_by(2).any(|i| n % i == 0)
}

fn main() {
    let limit = 1_000_000u64;

    // Sequential
    let seq_count = (2..limit).filter(|&n| is_prime(n)).count();
    println!("Primes < {} : {}", limit, seq_count);

    // Parallel — just swap iter() for par_iter()
    let par_count = (2u64..limit)
        .into_par_iter()
        .filter(|&n| is_prime(n))
        .count();
    println!("Parallel result: {}", par_count);
    assert_eq!(seq_count, par_count);
}
```
rayon's into_par_iter() distributes work across all CPU cores using work-stealing. The API is identical to sequential iterators — replacing iter() with par_iter() is the only change. Rayon automatically handles load balancing and thread lifecycle.

### Task
Implement a Rust HashMap-based graph with BFS traversal.

### Solution
```rust
use std::collections::{HashMap, HashSet, VecDeque};

struct Graph {
    edges: HashMap<u32, Vec<u32>>,
}

impl Graph {
    fn new() -> Self { Graph { edges: HashMap::new() } }

    fn add_edge(&mut self, from: u32, to: u32) {
        self.edges.entry(from).or_default().push(to);
        self.edges.entry(to).or_default().push(from);  // undirected
    }

    fn bfs(&self, start: u32) -> Vec<u32> {
        let mut visited = HashSet::new();
        let mut queue   = VecDeque::new();
        let mut order   = vec![];
        queue.push_back(start);
        visited.insert(start);
        while let Some(node) = queue.pop_front() {
            order.push(node);
            if let Some(neighbours) = self.edges.get(&node) {
                for &nb in neighbours {
                    if visited.insert(nb) {  // insert returns true if newly inserted
                        queue.push_back(nb);
                    }
                }
            }
        }
        order
    }
}

fn main() {
    let mut g = Graph::new();
    for (a,b) in [(1,2),(1,3),(2,4),(3,4),(4,5)] { g.add_edge(a,b); }
    println!("{:?}", g.bfs(1));  // [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
}
```
VecDeque provides O(1) push_back and pop_front — ideal for queues. HashSet::insert returns false if the value was already present, allowing the visited check and insert in one operation. or_default() inserts an empty Vec if the key is absent.

