### Task
Implement a Rust typed state machine using the typestate pattern.

### Solution
```rust
struct Locked;  struct Unlocked;  struct Open;

struct Safe<State> {
    contents: String,
    _state: std::marker::PhantomData<State>,
}

impl Safe<Locked> {
    fn new(contents: &str) -> Self {
        Safe { contents: contents.into(), _state: std::marker::PhantomData }
    }
    fn unlock(self, _pin: &str) -> Safe<Unlocked> {
        Safe { contents: self.contents, _state: std::marker::PhantomData }
    }
}

impl Safe<Unlocked> {
    fn open(self) -> Safe<Open> {
        Safe { contents: self.contents, _state: std::marker::PhantomData }
    }
    fn lock(self) -> Safe<Locked> {
        Safe { contents: self.contents, _state: std::marker::PhantomData }
    }
}

impl Safe<Open> {
    fn read(&self) -> &str { &self.contents }
    fn close(self) -> Safe<Unlocked> {
        Safe { contents: self.contents, _state: std::marker::PhantomData }
    }
}

fn main() {
    let safe = Safe::<Locked>::new("gold");
    let contents = safe.unlock("1234").open().read().to_string();
    println!("{}", contents);  // gold
    // safe.open();  // compile error: no `open` on `Locked`
}
```
Typestate pattern encodes valid state transitions in the type system — invalid sequences (opening a locked safe) are compile errors. PhantomData<State> makes State a zero-sized type parameter that exists only at compile time.

### Task
Debug and fix a Rust borrow checker error: returning a reference to a local.

### Solution
