Rust prevents dangling references at compile time — the local String is dropped when the function returns, so its reference would be invalid. Solutions: move ownership (return String), borrow from the caller's data, or use 'static for program-lifetime data.

### Task
Write Rust code implementing a simple in-memory key-value store with expiry using tokio.

### Solution
```rust
use std::collections::HashMap;
use std::sync::{Arc, Mutex};
use std::time::{Duration, Instant};
use tokio::time::sleep;

#[derive(Clone)]
struct Store {
    inner: Arc<Mutex<HashMap<String, (String, Instant)>>>,
}

impl Store {
    fn new() -> Self { Store { inner: Arc::new(Mutex::new(HashMap::new())) } }

    fn set(&self, key: &str, value: &str, ttl: Duration) {
        let exp = Instant::now() + ttl;
        self.inner.lock().unwrap().insert(key.into(), (value.into(), exp));
    }

    fn get(&self, key: &str) -> Option<String> {
        let mut map = self.inner.lock().unwrap();
        match map.get(key) {
            Some((v, exp)) if Instant::now() < *exp => Some(v.clone()),
            _ => { map.remove(key); None }
        }
    }
}

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() {
    let store = Store::new();
    store.set("k", "hello", Duration::from_millis(200));
    println!("{:?}", store.get("k"));   // Some("hello")
    sleep(Duration::from_millis(300)).await;
    println!("{:?}", store.get("k"));   // None
}
```
Arc<Mutex<T>> is the standard Rust pattern for shared mutable state across async tasks. Clone on Store clones the Arc (increments refcount) not the data. Lazy expiry removes entries on failed Get — avoids a background cleanup task for simple cases.

### Task
Implement Rust const generics for a fixed-size ring buffer.

### Solution
```rust
struct RingBuf<T, const N: usize> {
    data:  [Option<T>; N],
    head:  usize,
    len:   usize,
}

impl<T: Copy + Default, const N: usize> RingBuf<T, N> {
    fn new() -> Self {
        RingBuf { data: [None; N], head: 0, len: 0 }
    }

    fn push(&mut self, val: T) {
        let tail = (self.head + self.len) % N;
        self.data[tail] = Some(val);
        if self.len == N {
            self.head = (self.head + 1) % N;  // overwrite oldest
        } else {
            self.len += 1;
        }
    }

    fn pop(&mut self) -> Option<T> {
        if self.len == 0 { return None; }
        let item = self.data[self.head].take();
        self.head = (self.head + 1) % N;
        self.len -= 1;
        item
    }

    fn is_full(&self) -> bool { self.len == N }
}

fn main() {
    let mut rb: RingBuf<i32, 4> = RingBuf::new();
    for i in 1..=6 { rb.push(i); }
    while let Some(v) = rb.pop() { print!("{} ", v); }  // 3 4 5 6
}
```
Const generics (N: usize) allow the array size to be a type-level constant — no heap allocation, no Box. [None; N] requires T: Copy (for Copy-based array init) and Option<T>: Copy. The buffer wraps via modulo arithmetic.

